<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12017i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12017i">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12017i"> 17(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> druids in centre / &mdash; esses in isles / virgins in ile de Seine / Namnetes - m, visit H at / night in bark</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Leurs <mark>druides</mark> avaient leurs coll&egrave;ges <mark>au centre de la Gaule</mark>; <mark>les druidesses r&eacute;gnaient seules dans les &icirc;les</mark> de l&apos;Oc&eacute;an atlantique. Leurs r&egrave;gles variaient selon les coll&egrave;ges. <mark>A l&apos;&icirc;le de Seine</mark>, elles <font color="green">[146]</font> &eacute;taient vou&eacute;es &agrave; une <mark>virginit&eacute;</mark> perp&eacute;tuelle. A l&apos;embouchure de la Loire, au contraire, les pr&ecirc;tresses <mark>des Namn&egrave;tes &eacute;taient mari&eacute;s et visitaient</mark> leurs maris furtivement, <mark>&agrave; la nuit</mark> close, <mark>sur des barques</mark> l&eacute;g&egrave;res qu&apos;elles conduisaient elles-m&ecirc;mes. <br><font color="green">[Their druids had their colleges at the centre of Gaul; the druidesses reign alone on the islands in the Atlantic Ocean. Each college had its own rules. The ones on the island of Seine, they were devoted to a perpetual virginity. At the mouth of the Poire, on the contrary, the priestesses of the Namnetes were married and visited their husbands furtively, when night had come, in light boats they sailed themselves]</font> <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLL"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1892) 146-7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: According to Pomponius Mela, nine Celtic priestesses (druidesses), or <i>senes</i>, with magical powers lived on the Ile de Sein, a small island nine miles off the Pointe du Raz, at the tip of Brittany. </mm> </dd></dl>
